{"title_page": "Birbal", "text_new": "{{short description|Mughal advisor at Akbar's court, appearing in many folk tales which focus on his wit}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| title= [[Raja]] ([[Minister (government)|Mantri]]), [[Commander|Mukhytam mantri]], [[Sardar|Sard\u0101r of Akbar]]\n| image     = Birbal.jpg\n| alt       = Birbal\n| caption   = Birbal\n| birth_name  = Mahesh Das\n| birth_date  = 1528\n| birth_place = [[Kalpi]], Uttar Pradesh\n| death_date  = {{death year and age|1586|1528}}\n| death_place = [[Swat valley]], present-day [[Pakistan]]\n| religion    = <!-- He was a Din-i-ilahi follower And originally, He was a Vaishnava Hindu--> \n| occupation  = Main advisor in the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] court of Emperor [[Akbar]]\n| spouse = Urvashi Devi\n| issue = Saudamini (daughter)\n}}\n\n'''Birbal''' ({{IPA-ur|bi\u02d0rb\u0259l|IPA}}; born '''Mahesh Das'''; 1528{{ndash}}1586), or '''Raja Birbal''', was a Hindu advisor and main commander (mukhya senapati) of army in the court of the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor, [[Akbar]]. He is mostly known in the Indian subcontinent for the [[Fable|Folk Tales]] which focus on his [[wit]]. Birbal was appointed by Akbar as a Minister (Mantri) and used to be a Poet and Singer in around 1556\u20131562. He had a close association with Emperor [[Akbar]] and was one of his most important courtiers, part of a group called the ''[[navaratnas]]'' (nine jewels of Akbar). In 1586, Birbal led an army to crush an unrest in the north-west [[Indian subcontinent]] where he was killed along with many troops in an ambush by the rebel tribe. He was the only Hindu to adopt [[Din-i Ilahi]], the religion founded by Akbar.\n\nBy the end of Akbar's reign, local folk tales emerged involving his interactions with Akbar, portraying him as being extremely clever and witty. As the tales gained popularity in India, he became even more of a legendary figure across the Indian subcontinent. These tales involve him outsmarting rival courtiers and sometimes even Akbar, using only his intelligence and cunning, often with giving witty and humorous responses and impressing Akbar.\n\n==Early life==\nBirbal was born as Mahesh Das Brahmbhatt in 1528, to a [[Hindu]] [[Kayastha]] family<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gOkXAAAAIAAJ&q=Birbal+brahmin&dq=Birbal+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiR0Pvii6ffAhVHiHAKHcqgCzwQ6AEIUjAI Gayatri Rahasya: Or, An Exposition of the Gayatri]</ref> in [[Kalpi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India;<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbKv3zyIFD8C&lpg=PP1&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Cultural History of Medieval India |publisher=Berghahn Books |year=2007 |isbn=978-81-87358-30-5 |editor-last=Meenakshi Khanna |pages=24\u201344 |chapter=Section 1: Kingship and Court Mixing the Classic with the Folk}}</ref>{{rp|29}} according to folklore, it was at Tikawanpur near the banks of river [[Yamuna River|Yamuna]].<ref name=\"SubramaniamFolktales\">{{Cite book |last=Neela Subramaniam |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G5zqiW0Bd1YC&pg=PP2 |title=Birbal Stories (32 pp) |publisher=Sura Books |isbn=978-81-7478-301-1 |page=2 |access-date=30 June 2013}}</ref> His father was Ganga Das and mother, Anabha Davito. He was the third son of a [[Hindu]] [[Kayastha]] family<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|29}} which had a previous association with poetry and literature.<ref name=\"Frazer1898, Literary History\">{{Cite book |last=Robert Watson Frazer |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-MgkAAAAMAAJ |title=A Literary History of India |publisher=T.F. Unwin |year=1898 |page=359 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Ireland1834 Asiatic society\">{{Cite book |last=Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3MIsAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA698 |title=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland |year=1834 |page=698 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=June 2017}}\n\nEducated in [[Hindi]], [[Sanskrit]] and [[Persian language|Persian]], Birbal wrote prose, specialised in music and poetry in the [[Braj language|Braj]] language, thus gaining fame.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" /> He served at the [[Rajput]] court of Raja Ram Chandra of Rewa (Madhya Pradesh), under the name \"Brahma Kavi\". Birbal's economic and social status improved when he married the daughter of a respected and rich family, contrary to the notion that he was on poor economic terms before his appointment at Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]]'s imperial court.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" />\n\n==At the imperial court==\n\n===Titles and name origin===\n[[File:Mughal akbar.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Akbar was known to give his Hindu courtiers titles based on their cultural background.]]\nThe details and year of his first meeting with Akbar and his employment at the court are disputed but estimated to be between 1556 and 1562.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> He became the \"Kavi Priya\" ([[poet laureate]]) of the Emperor within a few years of his appointment.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\">{{Cite book |last=Beatrice K. Otto |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2BglxUD6Q6kC&pg=PA16 |title=Fools Are Everywhere: The Court Jester Around the World |date=1 April 2001 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=978-0-226-64091-4 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> Akbar bestowed upon him the name 'Birbal' with the title \"[[Raja]]\", by which he was known from then on.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" />\n\n''Birbal'' comes from ''Bir Bar'' or ''Vir Var'' which means courageous and great, quite contrary for him since he was not known for his bravery or for his military skill. Akbar gave titles to his Hindu subjects according to their traditions and S. H. Hodivala writes that it could have been taken from a character in the folk tale ''Vetal Panchvinshati''. This featured a courtier called Vir Var who showed great loyalty to his king. Akbar was also fond of literature, having works of Sanskrit and other local languages translated into Persian.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\">{{Cite book |last=Vicki K. Janik, Editor. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yLtoRB9Wy-sC&pg=PA91 |title=Fools and Jesters in Literature, Art, and History: A Bio-Bibliographical Sourcebook |date=1 January 1998 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-313-29785-4 |pages=91\u201396 |access-date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Position and association with Akbar===\nHis growing reputation led him to be part of Akbar's nine advisers, known as the [[Navaratnas|''Navaratna'']] - the nine jewels. Birbal also played the role of a religious advisor, military figure and close friend of the Emperor, serving him for 30 years.<ref name=\"Sharma1999 Mughal in India\">{{Cite book |last=S.R. Sharma |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4j_VLlGqVSoC&pg=PA787 |title=Mughal Empire in India: A Systematic Study Including Source Material |date=1 January 1999 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |isbn=978-81-7156-819-2 |page=787 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Malleson2001 Rise of Mughals\">{{Cite book |last=G. George Bruce Malleson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GwSF6l59x88C&pg=PA131 |title=Akbar and the Rise of the Mughal Empire |publisher=Cosmo Publications |year=2001 |isbn=978-81-7755-178-5 |pages=131, 160, 161 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> In 1572, he was among a large army sent to aid [[Sher Afghan Quli Khan|Husain Quli Khan]] against an attack from the Akbar's brother, [[Mirza Muhammad Hakim|Hakim Mirza]], which was his first military role. He later accompanied the Emperor during his [[Akbar#Annexation of Western and Eastern India|Gujarat campaigns]]. Despite having no military background, he often participated in Akbar's campaigns and was given leadership positions, like Todar Mal, who was an advisor in economic matters.<ref name=\"Advanced studies in medieval history\" />\n\n[[Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak]] and Abdul Qadir Badayuni were historians of the court. While Fazl respected him, listed him as having twenty five honorific titles and rank of a commander of two thousand; Badayuni distrusted Birbal because he was a Hindu, calling him a \"bastard\" and in contempt, writing how he, as a Hindu musician, was getting favour and becoming the king's \"[[confidant]]\", but at the same time acknowledging his talent.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> Akbar's other orthodox Muslim advisers were known to dislike Birbal.<ref name=\"Malleson2001 Rise of Mughals\" />\n\n[[File:Birbal's Palace.JPG|thumb|left|Birbal's house at [[Fatehpur Sikri]], he was the only courtier to get a special place near Akbar's palace.]]\nAkbar had started a religion called [[Din-i-Ilahi]], which acknowledged him as God's representative on earth and had a combination of Hindu and Muslim beliefs. In the ''Ain-i-Akbari ''(The Institutes of Akbar), it is mentioned that Birbal was one of the few people other than Akbar who were its followers, besides being the only Hindu.<ref name=\"History of Medieval Chauraisia\">{{Cite book |last=Radhey Shyam Chaurasia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XnaL7zPXPUC&pg=PA221 |title=History of Medieval India: From 1000 A.D. to 1707 A.D. |date=1 January 2002 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |isbn=978-81-269-0123-4 |pages=204\u2013221 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> He had a close association with Akbar, despite being fourteen years elder than him; of the nine ''ratnas'', Birbal was often called the brightest jewel.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" /> Badaoni referred to this in sarcasm, as \"a case of 'thy flesh is my flesh and thy blood my blood'\".<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> Akbar is reported to have saved Birbal's life in two instances.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|30}}\n\nThe painting ''Akbari Nao Ratna'' in Victoria hall, [[Kolkata]] depicts Birbal having a prominent position right next to Akbar. The Emperor found him entertaining at the start but in later years, sent him on important missions. Birbal was said to have received a two-storey house in [[Fatehpur Sikri]] within the palace complex,<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\">{{Cite book |last=Reddy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CeEmpfmbxKEC&pg=SL2-PA207 |title=Indian Hist (Opt) |date=1 December 2006 |publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education |isbn=978-0-07-063577-7 |pages=B\u2013 207, 236, D\u2013 13 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref>{{reliable|date=June 2017}}<ref name=\"Hindu:Fatehpur\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindigondia.com/2019/06/moral-stories-hindi.html |title=moral stories in hindi |last=hindigondia |website=hindigondia |access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> built close to Akbar's own chambers. He was said to enjoy having Birbal by his side and he was the only courtier to reside within the palace complex.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> One of the seven gates is known as \"Birbal's gate\".<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" />\n\n== Death ==\nThe Afghani [[Yousafzai]] tribes had started a rebellion along the east bank of [[river Indus]] against the Mughal rule. After troops sent to crush the unrest suffered losses, Akbar sent Birbal with reinforcements from his new fort at [[Attock]], to help the commander Zain-e- Khan in 1586. Birbal and the army advanced into a narrow pass in [[Swat valley]] (in present-day [[Pakistan]]) where the Afghanis were waiting in prepared positions in the hills.<ref name=\"SARIN2005 Akbar and Birbal\">{{Cite book |last=Amita Sarin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LN9ptrHH7EoC&pg=PT64 |title=Akbar and Birbal |date=21 March 2005 |publisher=Penguin Books Limited |isbn=978-81-8475-006-5 |page=64 |access-date=30 June 2013}}</ref>{{reliable|date=June 2017}} In the ensuing ambush and heavy defeat, Birbal and over 8000 soldiers were killed.<ref name=\"Richards1995 Mughal Empire\">{{Cite book |last=Richards |first=John F. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC&pg=PA49 |title=The Mughal Empire |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-521-56603-2 |pages=49\u201351 |author-link=John F. Richards |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> This was one of the largest military losses for Akbar.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" />{{reliable|date=June 2017}} He was said to have expressed his grief over the loss his favourite courtier and not taken food or drink for two days.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> He was anguished since his body could not be found for Hindu [[cremation]].<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" /> He proclaimed that it was his greatest tragedy since his coming to the throne.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" />\n\nBadayuni writes,<ref name=\"Advanced studies in medieval history\">{{Cite book |last=Mehta J L |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TsMl0vSc0gC&pg=PA264 |title=Advanced Study in the History of Medieval India-II |publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd |isbn=978-81-207-1015-3 |pages=264, 305, 321, 335 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><blockquote>His majesty cared for the death of no grandee more than for that of Birbal. He said, 'Alas! they could not even get his body out of the pass, that it might have been burned\"; but at last, he consoled himself with the thought that Birbal was now free and independent of all earthly fetters, and as the rays of the sun were sufficient for him, there was no necessity that he should be cleansed by fire.</blockquote>\n\n==Folklore and legacy==\n<!--\"Akbar and Birbal stories\" etc redirects here-->\n\n===Origins===\nAkbar-Birbal folk tales were passed on mainly by [[oral tradition]].<ref name=\"Havel, Handbook to Agra\">{{Cite book |last=E. B. Havell |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rBrmptxOsdgC&pg=PA49 |title=A Handbook to Agra and the Taj |date=1 August 2006 |publisher=Echo Library |isbn=978-1-4068-3384-3 |page=49 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=June 2017}} They focus on how Birbal manages to outsmart envious courtiers who try to trap and portray him in poor light in front of Akbar, often in a humorous manner with him shown giving sharp and intelligent responses. Others show his interactions with the Emperor which involve him trying to test Birbal's wit and Birbal making him realise his folly, which always ends with Akbar getting amused and impressed. He occasionally challenges Birbal by giving him a line of poetry which Birbal has to complete. Some of the other stories are simple humorous anecdotes. Getting an advantage in a seemingly impossible situation and making his challengers look silly are usual occurrences in these tales.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" />\n\nAccording to [[C. M. Naim]], the earliest known reference of Birbal's wit is in the 18th-century biographical dictionary, ''Ma'athir al-Umara'' in which he, thanks to his poetry and wit, becomes a member of the Akbar's inner circle and gradually outranks all other courtiers. Naim draws a parallel between the Akbar-Birbal tales with others in Indian folklore involving a king and his quick-witted minister such as the [[Vijaynagara]] emperor, [[Krishnadevaraya]] and [[Tenali Ramakrishna]] and King [[Krishnachandra Roy|Krishnachandra]] of [[Nadia Raj|Nadia]] and his barber, [[Gopal Bhar]].<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|35}} \nIn later years, a third character, [[Mulla Do-Piyaza]] began to appear. He was very likely a fictional character and was portrayed as Birbal's Muslim counterpart and a proponent of orthodox [[Islam]].<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|32}}\nHowever, when viewed within the context of folkloric literature, these stories, much like other similar tales like those of Krishnadevaraya and Tenali Rama, make fun of the human imperfections in the character of the king and then offer a corrective to his behaviour.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|xiv}}\n\n===Historic role versus folklore===\nIn the folk tales, he is always portrayed as a pious Hindu, being elder than Akbar, and being morally strict in the midst of opposing Muslim courtiers, who are shown plotting against him; his success was only because of his skill and he convinces the Emperor to favour Hinduism over Islam. He is thus depicted as acquiring religious, political and personal influence over Akbar, using his intelligence and sharp tongue and never resorting to violence. However, historically he never played such a role.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" /><ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" />\n\nBadayuni mistrusted him but did mention that he was \"having a considerable amount of capacity and genius\".<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" /> The Braj language poet, Rai Hol, praised Akbar and his nine jewels, having a special emphasis on Birbal for his generosity. Abul Fazl respected him by emphasising on his spiritual excellence and position as a confidant of the Emperor rather than on his wit or poetry.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />\n\nModern Hindu scholars assert that he made Akbar make bold decisions and the orthodox Muslims in the court despised him, since he made Akbar renounce Islam. But no evidence is present that he influenced Akbar's beliefs.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" /> Though sources suggest he influenced Akbar's policies to some extent. It was Akbar's affection for him, his religious tolerance and social liberalism which was the reason for this and Birbal was not the cause. Historically, he was more of a supporter of Akbar's religious policy and his religion, Din-i-Ilahi. ''Ain-i-Akbari'' mentions an incident involving prostitutes, where Akbar wanted to punish him, contrary to how he is portrayed as a deeply religious man.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />\n\n===In popular culture===\nAkbar and Birbal folk tales are featured in ''[[Amar Chitra Katha]]'' and ''[[Chandamama]]''<ref name=\"techtree\">{{Cite web |url=http://archive.techtree.com/techtree/jsp/article.jsp?article_id=85182&cat_id=643 |title=Chandamama Website is Revamped |date=13 December 2007 |publisher=techtree |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111153511/http://archive.techtree.com/techtree/jsp/article.jsp?article_id=85182&cat_id=643 |archive-date=11 November 2013 |access-date=3 July 2013}}</ref> children's comics and many books are available containing these collections.<ref name=\"BabbWadley1998 Media\">{{Cite book |last=Lawrence A. Babb |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cgDHFFe7YM8C&pg=PA107 |title=Media and the Transformation of Religion in South Asia |last2=Susan S. Wadley |date=1 January 1998 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1453-0 |page=107 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Tharoor2012\">{{Cite book |last=Shashi Tharoor |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KZkbZtvep8gC&pg=PT13 |title=Bookless in Baghdad: Reflections on Writing and Writers |date=1 April 2012 |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Inc. |isbn=978-1-61145-408-6 |pages=13, 14 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> There are various paperback editions, films, textbooks, booklets and plays with his character as the lead.<ref name=\"Datta1988 Indian Literature\">{{Cite book |last=Amaresh Datta |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zB4n3MVozbUC&pg=PA1607 |title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: devraj to jyoti |publisher=Sahitya Akademi |year=1988 |isbn=978-81-260-1194-0 |pages=1080, 1319, 1364, 1607 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> The television channel ''[[Cartoon Network]] ''in India'', ''has two featured animated series based on him, ''Chota Birbal'' and ''Akbar & Birbal.''<ref name=\"Hindu:Chota birbal\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/01/20/stories/2006012002220400.htm |title=Time now for Birbal and company |last=Sangeeta Barooah Pisharoty |website=The Hindu |access-date=3 July 2013}}</ref> [[Salman Rushdie's]] novel ''[[The Enchantress of Florence]] ''has the character of Birbal.<ref name=\"dailystar\">{{Cite web |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=169146 |title=Love among the Mughals |date=8 January 2011 |website=The Daily Star |access-date=3 July 2013}}</ref> ''[[Akbar Birbal]]'' is a 2014 historical comedy broadcast by [[Big Magic]].<ref name=\"HT\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/television/when-delnaz-irani-felt-like-a-queen/article1-1198857.aspx |title=When Delnaz Irani felt like a queen |date=22 March 2014 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=25 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425052533/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/television/when-delnaz-irani-felt-like-a-queen/article1-1198857.aspx |archive-date=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*''50 Wittiest Tales of Birbal'' ({{ISBN|81-7806-050-7}}) by Clifford Sawhney (Publishers: Pustak Mahal, Delhi).\n\n{{Humor and wit characters}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birbal}}\n[[Category:Mughal nobility]]\n[[Category:1528 births]]\n[[Category:1586 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Agra]]\n[[Category:Humour and wit characters of India]]\n[[Category:Hindi poets]]\n[[Category:Mughal Empire poets]]\n[[Category:Akbar]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mughal advisor at Akbar's court, appearing in many folk tales which focus on his wit}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| title= [[Raja]] ([[Minister (government)|Mantri]]), [[Commander|Mukhytam mantri]], [[Sardar|Sard\u0101r of Akbar]]\n| image     = Birbal.jpg\n| alt       = Birbal\n| caption   = Birbal\n| birth_name  = Mahesh Das\n| birth_date  = 1528\n| birth_place = [[Kalpi]], Uttar Pradesh\n| death_date  = {{death year and age|1586|1528}}\n| death_place = [[Swat valley]], present-day [[Pakistan]]\n| religion    = <!-- He was a Din-i-ilahi follower And originally, He was a Vaishnava Hindu--> \n| occupation  = Main advisor in the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] court of Emperor [[Akbar]]\n| spouse = Urvashi Devi\n| issue = Saudamini (daughter)\n}}\n\n'''Birbal''' ({{IPA-ur|bi\u02d0rb\u0259l|IPA}}; born '''Mahesh Das'''; 1528{{ndash}}1586), or '''Raja Birbal''', was a Hindu advisor and main commander (mukhya senapati) of army in the court of the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor, [[Akbar]]. He is mostly known in the Indian subcontinent for the [[Fable|Folk Tales]] which focus on his [[wit]]. Birbal was appointed by Akbar as a Minister (Mantri) and used to be a Poet and Singer in around 1556\u20131562. He had a close association with Emperor [[Akbar]] and was one of his most important courtiers, part of a group called the ''[[navaratnas]]'' (nine jewels of Akbar). In 1586, Birbal led an army to crush an unrest in the north-west [[Indian subcontinent]] where he was killed along with many troops in an ambush by the rebel tribe. He was the only Hindu to adopt [[Din-i Ilahi]], the religion founded by Akbar.\n\nBy the end of Akbar's reign, local folk tales emerged involving his interactions with Akbar, portraying him as being extremely clever and witty. As the tales gained popularity in India, he became even more of a legendary figure across the Indian subcontinent. These tales involve him outsmarting rival courtiers and sometimes even Akbar, using only his intelligence and cunning, often with giving witty and humorous responses and impressing Akbar.\n\n==Early life==\nBirbal was born as Mahesh Das Brahmbhatt in 1528, to a [[Hindu]] [[Kayastha]] family<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gOkXAAAAIAAJ&q=Birbal+brahmin&dq=Birbal+brahmin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiR0Pvii6ffAhVHiHAKHcqgCzwQ6AEIUjAI Gayatri Rahasya: Or, An Exposition of the Gayatri]</ref> in [[Kalpi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India;<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbKv3zyIFD8C&lpg=PP1&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Cultural History of Medieval India |publisher=Berghahn Books |year=2007 |isbn=978-81-87358-30-5 |editor-last=Meenakshi Khanna |pages=24\u201344 |chapter=Section 1: Kingship and Court Mixing the Classic with the Folk}}</ref>{{rp|29}} according to folklore, it was at Tikawanpur near the banks of river [[Yamuna River|Yamuna]].<ref name=\"SubramaniamFolktales\">{{Cite book |last=Neela Subramaniam |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G5zqiW0Bd1YC&pg=PP2 |title=Birbal Stories (32 pp) |publisher=Sura Books |isbn=978-81-7478-301-1 |page=2 |access-date=30 June 2013}}</ref> His father was Ganga Das and mother, Anabha Davito. He was the third son of a [[Hindu]] [[Kayastha]]- family<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|29}} which had a previous association with poetry and literature.<ref name=\"Frazer1898, Literary History\">{{Cite book |last=Robert Watson Frazer |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-MgkAAAAMAAJ |title=A Literary History of India |publisher=T.F. Unwin |year=1898 |page=359 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Ireland1834 Asiatic society\">{{Cite book |last=Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3MIsAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA698 |title=Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland |year=1834 |page=698 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=June 2017}}\n\nEducated in [[Hindi]], [[Sanskrit]] and [[Persian language|Persian]], Birbal wrote prose, specialised in music and poetry in the [[Braj language|Braj]] language, thus gaining fame.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" /> He served at the [[Rajput]] court of Raja Ram Chandra of Rewa (Madhya Pradesh), under the name \"Brahma Kavi\". Birbal's economic and social status improved when he married the daughter of a respected and rich family, contrary to the notion that he was on poor economic terms before his appointment at Mughal Emperor [[Akbar]]'s imperial court.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" />\n\n==At the imperial court==\n\n===Titles and name origin===\n[[File:Mughal akbar.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Akbar was known to give his Hindu courtiers titles based on their cultural background.]]\nThe details and year of his first meeting with Akbar and his employment at the court are disputed but estimated to be between 1556 and 1562.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> He became the \"Kavi Priya\" ([[poet laureate]]) of the Emperor within a few years of his appointment.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\">{{Cite book |last=Beatrice K. Otto |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2BglxUD6Q6kC&pg=PA16 |title=Fools Are Everywhere: The Court Jester Around the World |date=1 April 2001 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=978-0-226-64091-4 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> Akbar bestowed upon him the name 'Birbal' with the title \"[[Raja]]\", by which he was known from then on.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" />\n\n''Birbal'' comes from ''Bir Bar'' or ''Vir Var'' which means courageous and great, quite contrary for him since he was not known for his bravery or for his military skill. Akbar gave titles to his Hindu subjects according to their traditions and S. H. Hodivala writes that it could have been taken from a character in the folk tale ''Vetal Panchvinshati''. This featured a courtier called Vir Var who showed great loyalty to his king. Akbar was also fond of literature, having works of Sanskrit and other local languages translated into Persian.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\">{{Cite book |last=Vicki K. Janik, Editor. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yLtoRB9Wy-sC&pg=PA91 |title=Fools and Jesters in Literature, Art, and History: A Bio-Bibliographical Sourcebook |date=1 January 1998 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-313-29785-4 |pages=91\u201396 |access-date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Position and association with Akbar===\nHis growing reputation led him to be part of Akbar's nine advisers, known as the [[Navaratnas|''Navaratna'']] - the nine jewels. Birbal also played the role of a religious advisor, military figure and close friend of the Emperor, serving him for 30 years.<ref name=\"Sharma1999 Mughal in India\">{{Cite book |last=S.R. Sharma |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4j_VLlGqVSoC&pg=PA787 |title=Mughal Empire in India: A Systematic Study Including Source Material |date=1 January 1999 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |isbn=978-81-7156-819-2 |page=787 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Malleson2001 Rise of Mughals\">{{Cite book |last=G. George Bruce Malleson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GwSF6l59x88C&pg=PA131 |title=Akbar and the Rise of the Mughal Empire |publisher=Cosmo Publications |year=2001 |isbn=978-81-7755-178-5 |pages=131, 160, 161 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> In 1572, he was among a large army sent to aid [[Sher Afghan Quli Khan|Husain Quli Khan]] against an attack from the Akbar's brother, [[Mirza Muhammad Hakim|Hakim Mirza]], which was his first military role. He later accompanied the Emperor during his [[Akbar#Annexation of Western and Eastern India|Gujarat campaigns]]. Despite having no military background, he often participated in Akbar's campaigns and was given leadership positions, like Todar Mal, who was an advisor in economic matters.<ref name=\"Advanced studies in medieval history\" />\n\n[[Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak]] and Abdul Qadir Badayuni were historians of the court. While Fazl respected him, listed him as having twenty five honorific titles and rank of a commander of two thousand; Badayuni distrusted Birbal because he was a Hindu, calling him a \"bastard\" and in contempt, writing how he, as a Hindu musician, was getting favour and becoming the king's \"[[confidant]]\", but at the same time acknowledging his talent.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> Akbar's other orthodox Muslim advisers were known to dislike Birbal.<ref name=\"Malleson2001 Rise of Mughals\" />\n\n[[File:Birbal's Palace.JPG|thumb|left|Birbal's house at [[Fatehpur Sikri]], he was the only courtier to get a special place near Akbar's palace.]]\nAkbar had started a religion called [[Din-i-Ilahi]], which acknowledged him as God's representative on earth and had a combination of Hindu and Muslim beliefs. In the ''Ain-i-Akbari ''(The Institutes of Akbar), it is mentioned that Birbal was one of the few people other than Akbar who were its followers, besides being the only Hindu.<ref name=\"History of Medieval Chauraisia\">{{Cite book |last=Radhey Shyam Chaurasia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8XnaL7zPXPUC&pg=PA221 |title=History of Medieval India: From 1000 A.D. to 1707 A.D. |date=1 January 2002 |publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |isbn=978-81-269-0123-4 |pages=204\u2013221 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> He had a close association with Akbar, despite being fourteen years elder than him; of the nine ''ratnas'', Birbal was often called the brightest jewel.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" /> Badaoni referred to this in sarcasm, as \"a case of 'thy flesh is my flesh and thy blood my blood'\".<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> Akbar is reported to have saved Birbal's life in two instances.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|30}}\n\nThe painting ''Akbari Nao Ratna'' in Victoria hall, [[Kolkata]] depicts Birbal having a prominent position right next to Akbar. The Emperor found him entertaining at the start but in later years, sent him on important missions. Birbal was said to have received a two-storey house in [[Fatehpur Sikri]] within the palace complex,<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\">{{Cite book |last=Reddy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CeEmpfmbxKEC&pg=SL2-PA207 |title=Indian Hist (Opt) |date=1 December 2006 |publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education |isbn=978-0-07-063577-7 |pages=B\u2013 207, 236, D\u2013 13 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref>{{reliable|date=June 2017}}<ref name=\"Hindu:Fatehpur\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindigondia.com/2019/06/moral-stories-hindi.html |title=moral stories in hindi |last=hindigondia |website=hindigondia |access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> built close to Akbar's own chambers. He was said to enjoy having Birbal by his side and he was the only courtier to reside within the palace complex.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> One of the seven gates is known as \"Birbal's gate\".<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" />\n\n== Death ==\nThe Afghani [[Yousafzai]] tribes had started a rebellion along the east bank of [[river Indus]] against the Mughal rule. After troops sent to crush the unrest suffered losses, Akbar sent Birbal with reinforcements from his new fort at [[Attock]], to help the commander Zain-e- Khan in 1586. Birbal and the army advanced into a narrow pass in [[Swat valley]] (in present-day [[Pakistan]]) where the Afghanis were waiting in prepared positions in the hills.<ref name=\"SARIN2005 Akbar and Birbal\">{{Cite book |last=Amita Sarin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LN9ptrHH7EoC&pg=PT64 |title=Akbar and Birbal |date=21 March 2005 |publisher=Penguin Books Limited |isbn=978-81-8475-006-5 |page=64 |access-date=30 June 2013}}</ref>{{reliable|date=June 2017}} In the ensuing ambush and heavy defeat, Birbal and over 8000 soldiers were killed.<ref name=\"Richards1995 Mughal Empire\">{{Cite book |last=Richards |first=John F. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHyVh29gy4QC&pg=PA49 |title=The Mughal Empire |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-521-56603-2 |pages=49\u201351 |author-link=John F. Richards |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> This was one of the largest military losses for Akbar.<ref name=\"Reddy2006 Indian History\" />{{reliable|date=June 2017}} He was said to have expressed his grief over the loss his favourite courtier and not taken food or drink for two days.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" /> He was anguished since his body could not be found for Hindu [[cremation]].<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" /> He proclaimed that it was his greatest tragedy since his coming to the throne.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" />\n\nBadayuni writes,<ref name=\"Advanced studies in medieval history\">{{Cite book |last=Mehta J L |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TsMl0vSc0gC&pg=PA264 |title=Advanced Study in the History of Medieval India-II |publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd |isbn=978-81-207-1015-3 |pages=264, 305, 321, 335 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><blockquote>His majesty cared for the death of no grandee more than for that of Birbal. He said, 'Alas! they could not even get his body out of the pass, that it might have been burned\"; but at last, he consoled himself with the thought that Birbal was now free and independent of all earthly fetters, and as the rays of the sun were sufficient for him, there was no necessity that he should be cleansed by fire.</blockquote>\n\n==Folklore and legacy==\n<!--\"Akbar and Birbal stories\" etc redirects here-->\n\n===Origins===\nAkbar-Birbal folk tales were passed on mainly by [[oral tradition]].<ref name=\"Havel, Handbook to Agra\">{{Cite book |last=E. B. Havell |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rBrmptxOsdgC&pg=PA49 |title=A Handbook to Agra and the Taj |date=1 August 2006 |publisher=Echo Library |isbn=978-1-4068-3384-3 |page=49 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=June 2017}} They focus on how Birbal manages to outsmart envious courtiers who try to trap and portray him in poor light in front of Akbar, often in a humorous manner with him shown giving sharp and intelligent responses. Others show his interactions with the Emperor which involve him trying to test Birbal's wit and Birbal making him realise his folly, which always ends with Akbar getting amused and impressed. He occasionally challenges Birbal by giving him a line of poetry which Birbal has to complete. Some of the other stories are simple humorous anecdotes. Getting an advantage in a seemingly impossible situation and making his challengers look silly are usual occurrences in these tales.<ref name=\"Otto2001 Court Jester and world\" />\n\nAccording to [[C. M. Naim]], the earliest known reference of Birbal's wit is in the 18th-century biographical dictionary, ''Ma'athir al-Umara'' in which he, thanks to his poetry and wit, becomes a member of the Akbar's inner circle and gradually outranks all other courtiers. Naim draws a parallel between the Akbar-Birbal tales with others in Indian folklore involving a king and his quick-witted minister such as the [[Vijaynagara]] emperor, [[Krishnadevaraya]] and [[Tenali Ramakrishna]] and King [[Krishnachandra Roy|Krishnachandra]] of [[Nadia Raj|Nadia]] and his barber, [[Gopal Bhar]].<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|35}} \nIn later years, a third character, [[Mulla Do-Piyaza]] began to appear. He was very likely a fictional character and was portrayed as Birbal's Muslim counterpart and a proponent of orthodox [[Islam]].<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|32}}\nHowever, when viewed within the context of folkloric literature, these stories, much like other similar tales like those of Krishnadevaraya and Tenali Rama, make fun of the human imperfections in the character of the king and then offer a corrective to his behaviour.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />{{rp|xiv}}\n\n===Historic role versus folklore===\nIn the folk tales, he is always portrayed as a pious Hindu, being elder than Akbar, and being morally strict in the midst of opposing Muslim courtiers, who are shown plotting against him; his success was only because of his skill and he convinces the Emperor to favour Hinduism over Islam. He is thus depicted as acquiring religious, political and personal influence over Akbar, using his intelligence and sharp tongue and never resorting to violence. However, historically he never played such a role.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" /><ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" />\n\nBadayuni mistrusted him but did mention that he was \"having a considerable amount of capacity and genius\".<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" /> The Braj language poet, Rai Hol, praised Akbar and his nine jewels, having a special emphasis on Birbal for his generosity. Abul Fazl respected him by emphasising on his spiritual excellence and position as a confidant of the Emperor rather than on his wit or poetry.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />\n\nModern Hindu scholars assert that he made Akbar make bold decisions and the orthodox Muslims in the court despised him, since he made Akbar renounce Islam. But no evidence is present that he influenced Akbar's beliefs.<ref name=\"Fools and jesters\" /> Though sources suggest he influenced Akbar's policies to some extent. It was Akbar's affection for him, his religious tolerance and social liberalism which was the reason for this and Birbal was not the cause. Historically, he was more of a supporter of Akbar's religious policy and his religion, Din-i-Ilahi. ''Ain-i-Akbari'' mentions an incident involving prostitutes, where Akbar wanted to punish him, contrary to how he is portrayed as a deeply religious man.<ref name=\"Khanna, Culture of Medieval India\" />\n\n===In popular culture===\nAkbar and Birbal folk tales are featured in ''[[Amar Chitra Katha]]'' and ''[[Chandamama]]''<ref name=\"techtree\">{{Cite web |url=http://archive.techtree.com/techtree/jsp/article.jsp?article_id=85182&cat_id=643 |title=Chandamama Website is Revamped |date=13 December 2007 |publisher=techtree |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111153511/http://archive.techtree.com/techtree/jsp/article.jsp?article_id=85182&cat_id=643 |archive-date=11 November 2013 |access-date=3 July 2013}}</ref> children's comics and many books are available containing these collections.<ref name=\"BabbWadley1998 Media\">{{Cite book |last=Lawrence A. Babb |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cgDHFFe7YM8C&pg=PA107 |title=Media and the Transformation of Religion in South Asia |last2=Susan S. Wadley |date=1 January 1998 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1453-0 |page=107 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Tharoor2012\">{{Cite book |last=Shashi Tharoor |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KZkbZtvep8gC&pg=PT13 |title=Bookless in Baghdad: Reflections on Writing and Writers |date=1 April 2012 |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Inc. |isbn=978-1-61145-408-6 |pages=13, 14 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> There are various paperback editions, films, textbooks, booklets and plays with his character as the lead.<ref name=\"Datta1988 Indian Literature\">{{Cite book |last=Amaresh Datta |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zB4n3MVozbUC&pg=PA1607 |title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: devraj to jyoti |publisher=Sahitya Akademi |year=1988 |isbn=978-81-260-1194-0 |pages=1080, 1319, 1364, 1607 |access-date=29 June 2013}}</ref> The television channel ''[[Cartoon Network]] ''in India'', ''has two featured animated series based on him, ''Chota Birbal'' and ''Akbar & Birbal.''<ref name=\"Hindu:Chota birbal\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/01/20/stories/2006012002220400.htm |title=Time now for Birbal and company |last=Sangeeta Barooah Pisharoty |website=The Hindu |access-date=3 July 2013}}</ref> [[Salman Rushdie's]] novel ''[[The Enchantress of Florence]] ''has the character of Birbal.<ref name=\"dailystar\">{{Cite web |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=169146 |title=Love among the Mughals |date=8 January 2011 |website=The Daily Star |access-date=3 July 2013}}</ref> ''[[Akbar Birbal]]'' is a 2014 historical comedy broadcast by [[Big Magic]].<ref name=\"HT\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/television/when-delnaz-irani-felt-like-a-queen/article1-1198857.aspx |title=When Delnaz Irani felt like a queen |date=22 March 2014 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=25 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425052533/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/television/when-delnaz-irani-felt-like-a-queen/article1-1198857.aspx |archive-date=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*''50 Wittiest Tales of Birbal'' ({{ISBN|81-7806-050-7}}) by Clifford Sawhney (Publishers: Pustak Mahal, Delhi).\n\n{{Humor and wit characters}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birbal}}\n[[Category:Mughal nobility]]\n[[Category:1528 births]]\n[[Category:1586 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Agra]]\n[[Category:Humour and wit characters of India]]\n[[Category:Hindi poets]]\n[[Category:Mughal Empire poets]]\n[[Category:Akbar]]\n", "name_user": "Largoplazo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birbal"}
{"title_page": "List of board games", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a list of [[board game]]s. This page classifies board games according to the concerns which might be uppermost for someone organizing a gaming event or party. See the article on [[game classification]] for other alternatives, or see [[:Category:Board games|Category:Board games]] for a list of board game articles.\n\n==Single-player board games==\nSome board games have solo variants, like [[Arkham Horror]] and [[Agricola (board game)|Agricola]]. Others are specifically designed for one player.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n*[[Ambush!]]\n*[[B-17, Queen of the Skies]]\n*[[Fields of Fire (game)]]}}\n\n==Two-player abstract strategy games==\n{{main article|List of abstract strategy games}}\nIn [[abstract strategy game]]s, players know the entire game state at all times, and random generators such as dice are not used.\n\n==Two-player games==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n\n*[[Abalone (board game)|Abalone]]\n*[[Agon (game)|Agon]]\n*[[Android: Netrunner]]\n*[[Asalto]]\n*[[Backgammon]]\n*[[BattleLore (board game)]]\n*[[Battleship (game)|Battleship]]\n*[[Blockade (board game)|Blockade]]\n*[[Blood Bowl]]\n*[[Bul (game)|Bul]]\n*[[Camelot (board game)|Camelot]]\n*[[Chaturanga]] (Indian chess)\n*[[Checkers]]\n*[[Chess]]\n*[[Commands & Colors: Ancients]]\n*[[Connect 4]]\n*[[Cross and Circle game]]\n*[[Dald\u00f8s]]\n*[[Diamond (game)|Diamond]]\n*[[Diceball]]\n*[[Downfall (game)|Downfall]]\n*[[DVONN]]\n*[[Fanorona]]\n*[[Game of the Generals]]\n*[[Ghosts (board game)|Ghosts]]\n*[[Go (board game)|Go]]\n*[[GIPF (game)|Gipf]]\n*[[Guess Who?]]\n*[[Hare and Hounds (board game)|Hare and Hounds]]\n*[[Hounds and Jackals]]\n*[[Hex (board game)|Hex]]\n*[[Hijara]]\n*[[Isola (board game)|Isola]]\n*[[Janggi]] (Korean chess)\n*[[Jaipur (card game)|Jaipur]]\n*[[Le Jeu de la Guerre]]\n*[[Kalah]]\n*[[Kamisado]]\n*[[Liu po]]\n*[[Lost Cities]]\n*[[Mad Gab]]\n*[[Makruk]] (Thai chess)\n*[[Mastermind (board game)|Master Mind]]\n*[[Matching game]]\n*[[Nine men's morris]]\n*[[Onyx (game)|Onyx]]\n*[[Operation (game)|Operation]]\n*[[Ouk-Khmer (Hill's version)|Ouk Chatrang]] (Cambodian chess)\n*[[Plateau (game)|Plateau]]\n*[[P\u00dcNCT]]\n*[[Quarto (board game)|Quarto]]\n*[[Qwirkle]]\n*[[Rithmomachy]]\n*[[S\u00e1hkku]]\n*[[Santorini (game)|Santorini]]\n*[[Sector 41]]\n*[[Senet]]\n*[[Shatar]] (Mongolian chess)\n*[[Shatranj]] (Persian chess)\n*[[Shogi]] (Japanese chess)\n*[[Simon (game)|Simon]]\n*[[Sittuyin]] (Burmese chess)\n*[[Skip-Bo]]\n*[[Space Hulk]]\n*[[Star Wars: X-Wing Miniatures Game]]\n*[[Stratego]]\n*[[Sugoroku]]\n*[[Ta Y\u00fc]]\n*[[T\u00e2b]]\n*[[Tablut]]\n*[[Tantrix]]\n*[[Tak (game)|Tak]]\n*[[Twilight Struggle]]\n*[[Wari (game)|Wari]]\n*[[Wooper]]\n*[[Xiangqi]] (Chinese chess)\n*[[YINSH]]\n*[[Z\u00c8RTZ]]\n*[[Zingo!]]}}\n\n==Multi-player elimination games==\nParticipants are typically eliminated before game end.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n*[[13 Dead End Drive]]\n*[[1313 Dead End Drive]]\n*[[American Megafauna]]\n*[[Anti-Monopoly]]\n*[[Attack! (board game)|Attack!]]\n*[[Axis & Allies]]\n*[[Bang! (card game)|Bang!]]\n*[[Battle Sheep]]\n*[[Betrayal at House on the Hill]]\n*[[Blokus]]\n*[[Blood Feud in New York]]\n*[[Blue Max (board game)|Blue Max]]\n*[[Bookchase]]\n*[[Castle Risk]]\n*[[Clue Jr.: Case of the Missing Pet]]\n*[[Coppit]]\n*[[Diplomacy (game)|Diplomacy]]\n*[[Djambi]]\n*[[Doom: The Boardgame]]\n*[[Eclipse (board game)|Eclipse]]\n*[[The Farming Game]]\n*[[Finance (game)|Finance]]\n*[[Ghettopoly]]\n*[[Gl\u00fcckshaus]]\n*[[The Great Train Robbery (board game)|The Great Train Robbery]]\n*[[Heroscape]]\n*[[Hey, That's My Fish!]]\n*[[Hotels (board game)|Hotels]]\n*[[Jenga]]\n*[[Khet (game)|Khet]]\n*[[King of Tokyo]]\n*[[King Oil]]\n*[[Ludo (board game)|Ludo]]\n*[[Mikado (game)|Mikado]]\n*[[Monopoly (board game)|Monopoly]]\n*\n*[[Poleconomy]]\n*[[Risk (game)|Risk]]\n*[[Shadow Hunters]]\n*[[Shengguan Tu]]\n*[[Shogun (1986 board game)|Shogun